>>17010867
i never got him in the first place, it's a gacha game after all
the system is intentionally confusing, but the basic version is that you roll for a chance to get characters and every 20 days there's a new "banner" which makes it so that if you get a 5star (high rarity) character, it has a 50% chance to be one on the banner and a 50% chance to be an "evergreen" 5star from a small pool that never changes
so essentially if a character doesn't have a banner running then you have no way to get them. on the bright side, there's a pity counter so you're guaranteed to get a 5star by your 80th roll and you're also guaranteed never to get 2 evergreen 5stars in a row, so a lot of people just save up until they have 160 rolls before using any at all so they can be certain they'll get who they want. i'm just fast and loose with my rolling and have never gotten lucky while a venti banner is up
4star (low rarity) characters work on the same principles, but there's 3 of them to a banner and like 9 that you always have a chance to get

posts.com:
adhd is fundamentally an emotional problem. ppl online talk about "rejection sensitive dysphoria" & "emotional dysregulation" as if they're symptoms, but they're closer to the cause. speaking as someone who's struggled with adhd-pi symptoms for 30 years:

>shit happens to you as a kid
>being a kid with no coping skills, you're overwhelmed with painful emotion
>you don't get the emotional support you need from your parents
>you start to develop low self worth (as a kid with a simplistic view of the world, you assume your parents lack of interest in your emotions is somehow your fault for not being good enough)
>so you cope by closing yourself off to the painful emotions
>unfortunately it's all one valve, now you've accidentally closed yourself off to life-affirming, motivation-inducing positive emotions too (joy, admiration, desire etc)
>now you have no desire for anything in particular, other than a vague yearning for comfort (aka mother-love)
>without emotion, your world becomes gray, uninteresting
>now you have trouble "paying attention" because you have no desire
>motivated attention is what tells your brain that something is important enough to remember
>without interest in the world around you, memory problems start to develop
>you build up a catalog of failures and disappointments, which aggravates your lack of self-worth
>you try to compensate by throwing yourself into "projects"
>these "projects" are doomed to fail bc they're motivated by insecurity instead of desire, and because you cannot cope with the inevitable emotional fallout of confronting difficulty
>you develop addictions to sources of easy comfort (food, vidya, porn, scrolling, booze, weed)
>instead of doing the scary work of releasing & learning to deal with emotion, you vaguely intellectualize it as a "brain problem" and pop stimmies to feel good about staying on top of your laundry for once

Here is what I found: I can't use it when there is any lag in network service. I had an instance in a signal processing course where I needed to use a z-transform. In MATLAB the z-transform is in a separate software package outside the main MATLAB program. This package requires its own add-on license to be purchased separately from the main one. Every time it encounters the z-tranform in your code, MATLAB stops the program and phones home to verify your license to run the z-transform before running the z-transform and continuing with the program. If your external network connection fails or the network speed drops to low MATLAB will fail to validate the z-transform license and your program will be aborted with an error message about an illegal operation. It is honestly better to use SCILAB, OCTAVE, FORTRAN, or PYTHON.

>functions even are and how they work
this one specifically is much easier to conceptualize.
On the machine-code level, functions are broadly subroutines or macros(skipping a lot of complexity for normies)
subroutines: tell the program to jump to a certain point in memory which contains fixed instructions. The end of these instructions always tell the program to return back to its original location before the initial jump.
aka, jump to a certain location in memory that contains the litteraly ones and zeroes to run the function, then jump back when ur done

macros: copy/paste this template fixed instruction anywhere its called. ur program wont need to jump back and fourth in memory whenever a function is called.

broadly speaking, the tradeoff is as follow:
subroutines are 'slower' since ur jumping back and fourth between many places in memory, but your program is much 'smaller'(ur fixed instruction only exist at 1 place in memory)

macros are 'faster' since u dont make any jumps at all. All the function call u execute are directly copy/pasted within the machine code, but they are much 'larger'(copy/pasting repeats a lot of the same code, ur fixed instructions exist in repeated places in memory)

both R and Matlab are mostly good for visualizing and analyzing because they have good tools and libraries to draw well designed plots and graphs as well as run most common analyses in several fields with existing functions.

That said neither is superbly fast, efficient or error free so my recommendation is that if what you are doing is sufficiently complex and your script takes forever to run or you run into logic errors that are hard to find and solve, break up your work into parts and do as much as you can BEFORE you start using software tools. That is, write up your own script in a programming language you know (like Python for example) that does the crunching, spits out the data in the format you want it for analysis/presentation and saved in a file and then make a R/Matlab script to make pretty plots and analyses of that file that has your data neat and orderly and doesn't need tons of parsing and preprocessing.

And finally, the simplicity allows them to easily distinguish between who is a friend and who is an enemy—in other words, they can't be fooled like they would outside in the real world.

The conversations that take place are surface level, bordering on being small talk but contains a degree of personal honesty that would make these conversations impossible to have with strangers in person. What we have here is essentially a support system created by outcasts, for outcasts. True, that these threads do not contribute anything to /bant/'s already poor state, or does it help the outcasts overcome their situation. But should we mock people for trying to find comfort? I don't think so; it's simply very unproductive. As pathetic as they may seem, only an unsound mind could mock them.
